post_cb({"bq_ids": {"n4140": {"so_40563538_40563546_0": {"length": 20, "quality": 0.9523809523809523, "section_id": 5313}}, "n3337": {"so_40563538_40563546_0": {"length": 20, "quality": 0.9523809523809523, "section_id": 5110}}, "n4659": {"so_40563538_40563546_0": {"length": 20, "quality": 0.9523809523809523, "section_id": 6737}}}, "40563546": {"Id": "40563546", "PostTypeId": "2", "Body": "<p>There's no \"reason\" as such. That is how the language constructs were written. The syntax includes the usage of <code>;</code> as the authors mentioned.</p>\n<p>Just to quote a related paragraph from <code>C11</code>, chapter \u00a75.1.1.2, <em>Translation phases</em></p>\n<blockquote id=\"so_40563538_40563546_0\">\n<ul>\n<li>White-space characters separating tokens are no longer significant. Each\n  preprocessing token is converted into a token. The resulting tokens are\n  syntactically and semantically analyzed and translated as a translation unit.</li>\n</ul>\n</blockquote>\n<p>and, <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whitespace_character\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">newline is a whitespace</a>.</p>\n", "LastEditorUserId": "2173917", "LastActivityDate": "2016-11-12T14:10:24.903", "Score": "2", "CreationDate": "2016-11-12T13:53:51.357", "ParentId": "40563538", "CommentCount": "6", "OwnerUserId": "2173917", "LastEditDate": "2016-11-12T14:10:24.903"}, "40563538": {"ViewCount": "85", "Body": "<p>I've been using Groovy, and it seems to be able to handle similar C/C++ syntax without semicolons. My question is, why does C/C++ require semicolons? Is it to make compiling easier? Or are there actually ambiguities that I am unaware of (if so, please give examples)?</p>\n<p>This is to help aid in compiler design for my own language and am trying to decide if it required semicolons or not.</p>\n", "Title": "Why does C/C++ require semicolons?", "CreationDate": "2016-11-12T13:52:53.230", "Id": "40563538", "CommentCount": "5", "LastEditDate": "2016-11-12T14:11:18.010", "PostTypeId": "1", "LastEditorUserId": "2173917", "LastActivityDate": "2016-11-12T14:11:18.010", "Tags": "<c++><c><syntax>", "Score": "-3", "OwnerUserId": "3171100", "ClosedDate": "2016-11-12T13:56:20.073", "AnswerCount": "1"}});